\f5\fs30 \cf8 \cb3 \strokec8 For instance, in 2010, Nissan North America replaced its brand theme, \'93Shift,\'94 with the theme \'93Innovation for all.\'94 The word \'93Shift,\'94 however, still\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "http://mediadecoder.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/08/24/nissan-shifts-from-shift-to-innovation"}}{\fldrslt \cf9 \ul \ulc9 \strokec9 continues to appear}}\'a0in ads. And in 2007, when the actor Gary Sinise was hired to narrate commercials for the Army, succeeding the actor Josh Charles, the theme of the campaign remained \'93Army strong.\'94\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl450\partightenfactor0
\cf8 \cb3 The phrase \'93It\'92s what you do with what we do,\'94 while new to AT&T\'92s ads, echoes vintage ad themes that include \'93We do it all for you,\'94 for McDonald\'92s, and \'93We\'92d do it like you\'92d do it,\'94 for Burger King. (There is also a U-do We-do Laundromat in Philadelphia.)\cb1 \
