\f5\fs30 \cf8 \cb3 \strokec8 In two new commercials aimed at consumers, \'93It\'92s what you do with what we do\'94 is superimposed on screen near the end of each spot.\cb1 \
\cb3 In one commercial, an aspiring young actress named Alex gets a part, which an announcer sardonically describes as \'93the coveted role of \'91Coffee patron No. 4.\'92\'a0\'94 She subsequently seeks advice from family and friends on how she should deliver her one line, \'93Latte, please.\'94\cb1 \
\cb3 \'93Good thing AT&T gives you unlimited calling to any mobile,\'94 the announcer says, \'93so you can call everyone.\'94\cb1 \
\cb3 In the other commercial, a young man named Colin seeks to woo a young woman named Megan by showing off his new Lumia 900, much as years ago a guy would try to impress a girl by driving past her in his new Mustang II or Camaro SS 396.\cb1 \
\cb3 \'93See, Megan, Colin has lots of friends,\'94 an announcer says good-naturedly.\cb1 \
\cb3 There are also new commercials aimed at business customers. Spots for small businesses feature actual companies like Genco Services of McAllen, Tex., which rents heavy equipment. AT&T offers \'93a network of possibilities,\'94 an announcer says in the Genco spot, \'93helping you do what you do even better.\'94\cb1 \
\cb3 Business-to-business ads feature fictional firms like insurers, tow-truck operators and car-repair shops. \'93It\'92s the AT&T network,\'94 an announcer says, \'93doing more with data to help business do more for customers.\'94\cb1 \
\cb3 The budget for AT&T\'92s advertising is expected to be in line with what the company has spent in previous years. According to the AT&T 2011 annual report, the company spent $2.4 billion on advertising last year, $2.9 billion in 2010 and $2.8 billion in 2009.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\sl450\partightenfactor0
\cf8 \cb3 According to Kantar Media, AT&T was No. 2 in ad spending last year in the United States, behind only Procter & Gamble.\cb1 \
